  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Critique of Wang Anshi's Poem on Chrysanthemums
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have consulted the Poetry Talks of the Western Library and found therein a poem by Wang Anshi. It reads: 'In the twilight, wind and rain darken the garden, and withered chrysanthemums, scattered and falling, cover the earth with gold.' When Ouyang Xiu saw this, he remarked, 'All flowers fall, yet the chrysanthemum alone clings dried to its branch—how can one say it falls?' Ouyang Xiu's criticism was not entirely without merit, yet Wang Anshi flew into great rage and declared, 'This man knows not the Verses of Chu, which say: "At evening I feast upon the fallen petals of autumn chrysanthemums." This is Ouyang Xiu's failure of learning!'

    I offer this assessment: Poetry arises from what the poet has witnessed. I myself have once observed, in fierce wind and heavy rain, yellow chrysanthemums scatter and fall. Since Wang Anshi's poem already states 'in the twilight, wind and rain darken the garden,' his verse springs from genuine observation, and thus his rebuttal of Ouyang Xiu could stand. Yet to forcibly summon the Verses of Chu—it would have sufficed to say simply, 'Did Ouyang Xiu not witness this?' Why resort to calling it a failure of learning? Is such narrowness necessary? Even if Ouyang Xiu were not a man of vast and comprehensive learning, are the Verses of Chu some obscure and forgotten text that escaped his notice? Moreover, Ouyang Xiu was a celebrated scholar of his age—to accuse such a man of ignorance seems too severe. I cannot regard Wang Anshi as a person of true magnanimity.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Wang Anshi (王安石, 1021-1086) was a Northern Song statesman and poet; 'Wang Wengong' (王文公) was his posthumous title.
  - key: ''
    value: Ouyang Xiu (歐陽修, 1007-1072) was a celebrated Song scholar, historian, and critic known for his broad learning.
  - key: ''
    value: The Verses of Chu (楚辭) is an ancient Chinese literary anthology compiled during the Warring States period, associated with the region of Chu.
